---
/** Hub: Schedule H household-employer tax. Worked example from the same lib as the island. */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import NannyTaxCalculator from '../../components/calculators/NannyTaxCalculator.tsx';
import { nannyTax, HOUSEHOLD_THRESHOLD, SS_WAGE_BASE } from '../../lib/household-employer';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const ex = nannyTax({ wages: 40000, tips: 0, fedWithheld: 0, stateWithheld: 0, sutaRate: 0.034, sutaWageBase: 7000, sutaPaidOnTime: true, futaCreditReduction: 0 });
---

<Base
  title="Nanny tax calculator 2026 (Schedule H)"
  description="What you owe as a household employer in 2026: employer Social Security, Medicare, FUTA and state unemployment tax on a nanny or caregiver's wages."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year · Schedule H</p>
    <h1>Nanny / household employer tax calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">Pay a nanny, housekeeper or caregiver over the threshold and you are their employer — with Social Security, Medicare and unemployment taxes to match. Here is the real cost.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    Hire someone to work in your home and control how they do it, and they are your employee, not a contractor.
    Once cash wages reach {formatMoney(HOUSEHOLD_THRESHOLD)} in 2026 you owe the "nanny tax": employer Social
    Security and Medicare, federal unemployment tax (FUTA), and state unemployment tax (SUTA). It all goes on
    Schedule H with your own Form 1040.
  </p>

  <NannyTaxCalculator client:load />

  <h2>What you actually owe</h2>
  <p>
    Employer FICA is 7.65% of wages — 6.2% Social Security up to the {formatMoney(SS_WAGE_BASE)} wage base, plus
    1.45% Medicare with no cap. FUTA is 6% of the first $7,000, but paying your state unemployment tax on time
    earns a 5.4% credit that drops it to just 0.6%. Miss that deadline and the full 6% applies.
  </p>

  <h2>Worked example</h2>
  <p>A nanny paid {formatMoney(40000)} in a state with a 3.4% SUTA rate on a $7,000 base, state tax paid on time:</p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Employer tax</th><th>Amount</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Employer Social Security (6.2%)</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.employerSS)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Employer Medicare (1.45%)</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.employerMedicare)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>FUTA (0.6% of first $7,000)</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.futaTax)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>State unemployment (SUTA)</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.sutaTax)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Total employer taxes</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.totalEmployerTaxes)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Total cost to you (wages + taxes)</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.totalCostToEmployer)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The {formatMoney(40000)} of wages actually costs you {formatMoney(ex.totalCostToEmployer)} — about
    {' '}{formatMoney(ex.totalEmployerTaxes)} in employer taxes on top. Separately, you withhold the employee's
    own {formatMoney(ex.employeeFICA)} FICA share from their pay; you do not pay that, they do.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>When do I have to file Schedule H?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      If you paid any one household employee {formatMoney(HOUSEHOLD_THRESHOLD)} or more in cash wages in 2026, or
      you withheld federal income tax for them. You file Schedule H with your Form 1040 by the April deadline.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Why does FUTA jump from 0.6% to 6%?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      The 6% federal rate comes with a credit of up to 5.4% for state unemployment tax paid on time — leaving a
      net 0.6%. The credit is the full 5.4% even if your state rate is lower, as long as you pay the state on
      time. Miss the state deadline and you lose the credit, so the federal rate reverts to the full 6%.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Is my nanny an employee or a contractor?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      Almost always an employee. If you control what work is done and how — hours, tasks, methods — the IRS
      treats them as your employee, and issuing a 1099 does not change that. Independent contractor status is
      for workers who run their own business and set their own methods, which a household nanny rarely does.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What does the employee's share cover?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      You withhold their 7.65% FICA from their pay and remit it with your employer share, so the government gets
      the full 15.3%. Those contributions build the employee's Social Security and Medicare credits — the reason
      paying "under the table" quietly costs the worker their future benefits.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/child-care-tax-credit-calculator/">Child care tax credit</a> — offset some of this cost</li>
